Paul Hunter et al. estimated that COVID-19, which appears to be much more contagious than SARS, would not end in 2020.
Ira Longini and others created a model for predicting the outcome of the epidemic and suggested that SARS-Cove-2 could infect two-thirds of the world's population.
A Canadian group reported that SARS-CoV-2 was discovered in mid- and throat oyster swabs for patients who recovered and left the hospital 2 weeks ago, suggesting the newly discovered virus could become a flu-like cyclical seizure.
However, promising signs have emerged in China based on the number of new cases declining, which suggests that current strategies may have worked.
Ebola was originally expected to cause up to a million cases with half a million deaths.
However, the disease was eventually controlled by strict quarantine and isolation measures.
It is possible, like SARS-CoV, that SARS-CoV-2 becomes weaker in terms of causing infection and eventually goes away or becomes a less pathogenic virus that coexists with humans.
